SIMPLE: junket
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Junket
<hw>Jun"ket</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly also
<ets>juncate</ets>, fr. It. <ets>giuncata</ets> cream cheese, made in a
wicker or rush basket, fr. L. <ets>juncus</ets> a rush. See 2d
<er>Junk</er>, and cf. <er>Juncate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A cheese cake; a sweetmeat; any delicate
food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How Faery Mab the <qex>junkets</qex> eat.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Victuals varied well in taste,⟦br⟧
And other <qex>junkets</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A feast; an entertainment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A new jaunt or <qex>junket</qex> every night.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A trip made at the expense of an organization of
which the traveller is an official, ostensibly to obtain information
relevant to one's duties; especially, a trip made by a public official
at government expense. The term is sometimes used opprobriously, from a
belief that such trips are often taken for private pleasure, and are
therefore a waste of public money; <as>as, a congressional
<ex>junket</ex> to a tropical country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Junket</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Junket
<hw>Jun"ket</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To feast; to banquet; to make an
entertainment; -- sometimes applied opprobriously to feasting by public
officers at the public cost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Job's children <qex>junketed</qex> and feasted together often.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Junket</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Junket
<hw>Jun"ket</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Junketed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Junketing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To give entertainment to; to
feast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The good woman took my lodgings over my head, and was in such a
hurry to <qex>junket</qex> her neighbors.</q>
<rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Junketing</ent>⟦br⟧
